T1  - The Foreign Dependence Question
AU  - Tolley, George S.
AU  - Wilman, John D.
Y1  - 1977/04/01
PY  - 1977
DA  - 1977/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260565
DO  - 10.1086/260565
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 323
EP  - 347
VL  - 85
IS  - 2
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - An embargo probability leads to private adjustments to curtail consumption and expand production, raising marginal value of consumption less than of production. If there are unemployment or foreign policy externalities, there is an optimal tariff which is proportional to foreign dependence, is inversely proportional to elasticity of external embargo loss, varies directly with embargo probability, and depends more complexly on other parameters. Stockpiling should limit embargo price rise to unit cost of storage divided by embargo frequency. With low embargo frequency, the price rise based on the stockpiling criterion may be greater than with no stockpiling. is then unwarranted.
AB  - An embargo probability leads to private adjustments to curtail consumption and expand production, raising marginal value of consumption less than of production. If there are unemployment or foreign policy externalities, there is an optimal tariff which is proportional to foreign dependence, is inversely proportional to elasticity of external embargo loss, varies directly with embargo probability, and depends more complexly on other parameters. Stockpiling should limit embargo price rise to unit cost of storage divided by embargo frequency. With low embargo frequency, the price rise based on the stockpiling criterion may be greater than with no stockpiling. is then unwarranted.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/260565
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/260565
Y2  - 2024/03/23
