TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Surprising Incidence of a Tax on Pure Rent: A New Answer to an Old Question
AU  - Feldstein, Martin
Y1  - 1977/04/01
PY  - 1977
DA  - 1977/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260566
DO  - 10.1086/260566
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 349
EP  - 360
VL  - 85
IS  - 2
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - The classic example of an unshiftable tax is the general tax on pure rental income. Since Ricardo, economists have believed that the annual net rental income of unimproved land falls by the amount of the annual tax and its price by the capitalized value of this tax. This paper shows that these conclusions are false, that the tax on pure land rents is at least partly shifted, and that the price of land may be increased by the imposition of a tax. Implications are suggested for the analysis of the corporate income tax and the taxation of natural resources.
AB  - The classic example of an unshiftable tax is the general tax on pure rental income. Since Ricardo, economists have believed that the annual net rental income of unimproved land falls by the amount of the annual tax and its price by the capitalized value of this tax. This paper shows that these conclusions are false, that the tax on pure land rents is at least partly shifted, and that the price of land may be increased by the imposition of a tax. Implications are suggested for the analysis of the corporate income tax and the taxation of natural resources.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/260566
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/260566
Y2  - 2024/03/23
